Paving the way for healing and renewal. That’s Sibanye-Stillwater's hope for Marikana. An investment by the company of almost R4-billion will create over 4,000 additional jobs and is about to get underway.eNCA's Govan Whittles reports. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Sibanye-Stillwater hopes to pave a way for healing and renewal for Marikana. An investment by the company, of almost R4-billion will create over 4,000 additional jobs and is about to get underway. READ: Marikana massacre: Survivor wants to see Ramaphosa in court The Mining Group has started engaging with multiple stakeholders involved in the project. Archbishop, Thabo Makgopa says Marikana Renewal Project must help the community rise again. The massacre plunged the mine into turmoil, but Sibanye-Stillwater says it has finally turned the corner.